{"_id":"OGZiNTg1MzAzYjg1","name":"What Sildar Knows","permission":{"default":0},"folder":"MWU2YzY0Njg5ZDA0","flags":{"R20Converter":{"handout-order":3,"handout-archived":false}},"sort":30000,"entryTime":0,"content":"If the party manages to save Sildar and heal him back to consciousness, he is able to provide four pieces of useful information:<br><br><ul><li>The three Rockseeker brothers (Gundren, Tharden, and Nundro) recently located an entrance to the long-lost Wave Echo Cave, site of the mines of the Phandelver’s Pact. (Share the information in the first two paragraphs of the “Background” section to the players at this time.)</li></ul><br><ul><li>Klarg, the bugbear who leads this goblin band, had orders to waylay Gundren. Sildar heard from the goblins that the Black Spider sent word that the dwarf was to be brought to him. Sildar doesn’t know who or what the Black Spider is.</li></ul><br><ul><li>Gundren had a map showing the secret location of Wave Echo Cave, but the goblins took it when they captured him. Sildar believes that Klarg sent the map and the dwarf to the chief of the Cragmaws at a place called Cragmaw Castle. Sildar doesn’t know where that might be, but he suggests someone in Phandalin might know. (It doesn’t occur to Sildar immediately, but a captured goblin might also be persuaded to divulge the castle’s location. See the <a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=JournalEntry data-id=MzgyOWUwYjFiMWVk ><i class=\"fas fa-book-open\"></i>What the Goblins Know</a> handout.)</li></ul><br><ul><li>Sildar’s contact in Phandalin is a human wizard named Iarno Albrek. The wizard traveled to the town two months ago to establish order there. After the Lords’ Alliance received no word from Iarno, Sildar decided to investigate.</li></ul>","img":""}
{"_id":"OTA4MjZkNGViYTU4","name":"Important Phandalin NPCs","permission":{"default":0},"folder":"MjAyZjQxNDQ1Mjkz","flags":{"R20Converter":{"handout-order":1,"handout-archived":false}},"sort":10000,"entryTime":0,"content":"Here is a quick summary of the most important NPCs in Phandalin, and their relevance to the adventure.<br><br><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=N2ZkZDZhYTAyNmVm ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Toblen Stonehill</a> - Innkeeper</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=NTk5OGIwMDFkMjI3 ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Elmar Barthen</a> - Owns a trading post; owes money to the party if you are using the Gunden adventure hook</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=NGU4Mzk4MzBiNTMz ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Daran Edermath</a> - Member of the Order of the Gauntlet with a quest for the party</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=OWViYzNmMmM1ZWUx ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Linene Graywind</a> - Runs a trading post and offers a reward for retrieving her supplies</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=ZTZlOWE2OGVlNjg3 ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Halia Thornton</a> - Member of the Zhentarim with a quest for the party</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=MTVlZTQzOGEyYzNh ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Qelline Alderleaf</a> - Helpful halfling farmer whose son, Carp, knows a secret way into the Redbrands’ hideout</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=NDQ0MTJkY2IwNTE3 ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Sister Garaele</a> - Elf cleric of Tymora and Harper agent with a quest for the party</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=NTMyNDYwOGVlYzQ5 ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Harbin Wester</a> - Townmaster of Phandalin with a quest for the party</li></ul><ul><li><a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=Actor data-id=NGMyYzJjZWNlZDFi ><i class=\"fas fa-user\"></i>Sildar Hallwinter</a> - Member of the Lords’ Alliance with two quests for the party</li></ul><br><h4>Roleplaying Phandalin NPCs</h4>If you’re not sure how to run an NPC, a good way to start is to have the character introduce himself or herself, welcome the adventurers to Phandalin, and ask who they are and what they want. You don’t need to be an actor or stand-up comedian to get good drama or humor out of your NPCs, but if you want to ham it up, here’s some advice:<br><br><strong><em>Relax:</em></strong> Don’t worry about impressing your players with your thespian skills (or lack thereof).<br><br><strong><em>Get inside the NPCs’ minds:</em></strong> Imagine how they might react to the characters, and strive to be realistic.<br><br><strong><em>Mug it up:</em></strong> Scowl, smile, snarl, flutter your eyelashes, pout, cross your eyes, rub your hands together—whatever it takes to make your NPCs come to life.<br><br><strong><em>Try different voices:</em></strong> Borrow distinctive speech patterns from real life, movies, and television. Adjust the volume as appropriate. An NPC can be loud, soft-spoken, or something in between.<br><br><strong><em>Keep the game moving:</em></strong> Let the players steer the interactions with the NPCs.<br><br>The characters have no reason to fight ordinary townsfolk. Hence, no game statistics are provided for them. If statistics become necessary, use the commoner stat block to represent an adult NPC of any race.","img":""}
{"_id":"OTBjZDAyMjJmN2My","name":"Adventure Overview","permission":{"default":0},"folder":"MzJjNGJlZDhiZDJm","sort":230000,"flags":{"R20Converter":{"handout-order":2,"handout-archived":false}},"content":"<h3>Playing Lost Mine of Phandelver in Roll20</h3>Contained in this Roll20 Campaign is all the components needed to play the Lost Mine of Phandelver adventure that comes with the <em>Dungeons &amp; Dragons 5th Edition Starter Set</em>. Meant as an introduction to Dungeons &amp; Dragons, this campaign runs hand-in-hand with the <a href=\"http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/basicrules\"><em>Player's Dungeons &amp; Dragons Basic Rules</em></a>, which is available completely free from WotC's website. You can download your own copy of the PDF <a href=\"https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/basicrules\">HERE</a>.<br><br>For your convenience, this campaign's handouts list page and chapter numbers from the above PDF so you and your players can refer back to specific rules mentioned throughout this adventure.<br><br><h4>Dynamic Lighting</h4>All of the floor maps provided for this adventure has <a href=\"https://wiki.roll20.net/Dynamic_Lighting\">Dynamic Lighting</a> enabled. This is an advanced feature available to only <strong>Plus</strong> &amp; <strong>Pro</strong> Roll20 Users. If you are a Base Subscriber, you can still hide areas of your floor map by using the <a href=\"https://wiki.roll20.net/Fog_of_War\">Fog of War Tool</a>.<br><br>The Elf Wizard and Dwarf Cleric tokens have been set up at default to have Darkvision range for vision. Both Human Fighters and the Halfling Rogue tokens are currently all set to be holding a torch. You'll want to adjust the light radius on those tokens as you discern who's holding a torch during adventuring. You can read up on dynamic lighting for <a href=\"https://wiki.roll20.net/Dynamic_Lighting_Examples#Dungeons_and_Dragons_5th_Edition\">5th Edition here</a>.<br><br><h4>Player Tokens</h4><span style=\"color: rgb( 0 , 0 , 0 )\">The PC Tokens displayed on the Landing Page are <a href=\"https://wiki.roll20.net/Card_Decks_and_Rollable_Tables#Rollable_Tables\">Rollable Table Tokens</a> so each player can choose between various different male and female portraits for their PCs. You're also welcome to incorporate whatever tokens your players would like to use for their characters. Token permissions are tied to their respective character sheets.<br><br>If you're new to Roll20, we recommend copying and pasting player tokens from one map to the next instead of dragging them out from the Journal. This will make it possible to retain the chosen portraits for each PC. <br><br>If you're well familiar with Roll20, once players have chosen their desired portrait and renamed their tokens, you can re-link them to their character sheets. This retains the chosen side of the token and makes dragging the journal entries possible. </span><br><hr><h3>Adventure Backstory </h3>Over five hundred years ago, a pact was made between a clan of gnomes and dwarves which became known as the Phandelver Pact. Together they mined the magically rich ores within Wave Echo Cave. Human spellcasters from nearby Phandalin joined forces with them and together they combined their collective skills to create a forge to craft magical items dubbed the Forge of Spells. Everything came to an abrupt end when orcs, craving magical treasures, sieged Phandalin and the Wave Echo Cave mine. The battle destroyed Phandalin and much of the mine as well, causing various cave-ins throughout. Very few survived the conflict to relate the tale. The Forge of Spells become legend and the entrance to Wave Echo Cave was lost.<br><br>Flash-forward to present day, th<span style=\"color: rgb( 0 , 0 , 0 )\">e Rockseeker brothers, </span>intent in finding and reopening this now-fabled mine, manage to locate the cave. Their activity was never a secret. A nefarious villain known as Nezznar the Black Spider, a drow wizard, has been watching and waiting for the dwarves to uncover this location. The drow desires to harness the Forge of Spells for his own purposes and has rallied bandit gangs and goblin tribes from within the region to aid him in this mission. The party's questing within the Sword Coast region will have them square off with various underlings of Nezznar's and eventually the drow himself if they choose to pursue him straight into the Wave Echo Cave.<br><br><h3>Act 1: Goblin Arrows <a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=JournalEntry data-id=OTQwODFiYzMyYTAx ><i class=\"fas fa-book-open\"></i>Overview Link</a></h3><strong>Summary:</strong> The party is sent off to the town of Phandalin and along the way, they encounter the destroyed remains of a trader's wagon. While investigating, goblins ambush the party. If the party chooses to track the goblins into the woods they will find a cave that is a hideout for the Cragmaw goblin tribe. If they're quick-witted, the party can save Sildar Hallwinter, a human warrior who was aboard the previously assaulted wagon. The other member who was on that wagon, a dwarf named Gundren Rockseeker, has been taken away elsewhere. The party continues on to Phandalin.<br><br><strong>Maps Used:</strong> <br><ul><li>Sword Coast Map</li><li>1: Goblin Ambush</li><li>2: Cragmaw Hideout</li></ul><br><h3>Act 2: Phandalin <a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=JournalEntry data-id=N2FjNDQ1Mjk4ZWEw ><i class=\"fas fa-book-open\"></i>Overview Link</a></h3><strong>Summary:</strong> The town of Phandalin is a ramshackle village built around the remains and foundations of the previous settlement destroyed by an orc warband hundreds of years previous. The party can learn more about <span style=\"color: rgb( 0 , 0 , 0 )\">Gundren and</span> his two brothers, Tharden and Nundro Rockseeker. All three have recently mysteriously vanished since making the claim that they had located an entrance to the legen<span style=\"color: rgb( 0 , 0 , 0 )\">dary Wave Echo Cave. T</span>hings are clearly amiss in town when the party arrives. The denizens of Phandalin are being terrorized by a gang of bandits dubbed The Redbrands, named as such for the scarlet cloaks they all wear. The party can accept several side quests around town and enquire about the Rockseeker brothers. Eventually, their activity attracts the attention of the Redbrands who are keen on either running the party out of town or killing them outright. The party is forced to handle the Redbrands in order to remain in Phandalin, which leads them to infiltrating the Redbrand Hideout and sussing out their leader, the charismatic Glasstaff, to put an end to the bandit gang. <br><br><strong>Maps Used:</strong><br><ul><li>3: Phandalin</li><li>4: Redbrand Hideout</li></ul><br><h3>Act 3: The Spider's Web <a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=JournalEntry data-id=YWFkZjA3OTAwOTdh ><i class=\"fas fa-book-open\"></i>Overview Link</a></h3><strong>Summary:</strong> In this arc of the campaign, the players can participate in any or <em>all</em> of the side quests given out by various villagers of Phandalin. Each side quest will task the party to venture out into the surrounding forests of the Sword Coast region to explore a specific location.The only side quest that is essential to this act in the campaign is Cragmaw Castle. All other side quests can be completed either during this act OR after this campaign is over to lead onto new adventures.<br>Hints on the whereabouts of Gundren Rockseeker lead the party to Cragmaw Castle, an old fort reclaimed by the Cragmaw goblin tribe. Gundren is being held prisoner here and can be freed after defeating the Cragmaw's leader King Grol and his wolf companion, Snarl. Fearful for the safety of his siblings, Gundren is eager to lead the party to the Wave Echo Cave. <br><br><strong>Maps Used:</strong><br><ul><li>Sword Coast Map</li><li>Ruins of Thundertree (optional side quest)</li><li>5: Cragmaw Castle</li></ul><br><h3>Act 4: Wave Echo Cave <a class=\"entity-link\" data-entity=JournalEntry data-id=YmFjODNiN2Q5NWEz ><i class=\"fas fa-book-open\"></i>Overview Link</a></h3><strong>Summary:</strong> It is clear now that all the goblins and bandits wreaking havoc in the area are taking orders from someone calling themself the Black Spider. This mystery villain is intent on making sure the location to Wave Echo Cave is kept secret and is the reason why the dwarven siblings were kidnapped. The party ventures into Wave Echo Cave to find the other two Rockseeker brothers. They'll need to defeat various monsters and face off with Nezznar The Black Spider, but their efforts will be rewarded with lost treasures and the Forge of Spellsitself! Completing Wave Echo Cave is the end of the <em>Lost Mine of Phandelver</em> campaign of the D&amp;D 5e Starter Set, but it leaves many loose threads dangling for a Dungeon Master to tug on to create new adventures for their players. <br><br><strong>Maps Used:</strong><br><ul><li>6: Wave Echo Cave</li></ul>","img":""}
